Scottish private schools maintain a track record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with outstanding exam results, further reinforced by each student and collective success in sports, arts, music as well as hard work.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Board of Private Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the best service for students and parents.
The independent school aims to prepare its students for further and higher education, their chosen careers, and their role as citizens of the world.
As an education sector that can design and implement school curriculums as expected, we see modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable choice subject in many schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language he understands, your speech goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, your words will come to his heart.”
It’s a strong reminder that we can’t just rely on English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year’s latest exam, we can see that language is the top position of the league table with the highest graduation scores in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learn a foreign language get an A Plus grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72 percent of students received an A Plus in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent who learned Spanish also received an A.
This suggests that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as an important skill that children and adolescents will need in the future.
Today the languages, as a choice of subjects, are held in the same standard as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in modern school curriculum and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Service in 2014 found that from several reasons why employers should continue to struggle to fill vacancies, 17 percent of the reason is a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly encouraged to prepare teenagers for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Whatever a person’s career choice, if they have already learned a second language, in the future they will feel the real benefits of having this kind of lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with residents of foreign countries will automatically make a multilingual superior in the competition.
According to a YouGov poll of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent of them did not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French became the only language spoken in double-digit percentage, which was 15 percent.
This is why investing in language teaching for today’s children is important for now.
Having multilingual skills, especially the language of countries with developing economies, will equip children with better opportunities to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach a different language.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach the language considered the most important in the UK for the next few years, i.e. 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff who are experts in the field.
Scottish independent schools are aimed at providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what happens in the future.
It is undeniable that today, in a global business environment, language will always be an important aspect in determining a country’s future, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence to Scottish teens.
Il fait bien le juste.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Independent School Board.
