Harvard students take courses about adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year puts all of the undergraduate students there to more sleep, in a bid to fight a macho culture in developing learning through a caffeine-powered ‘owl man’.
One academic found that students at the world’s number one universities often don’t know anything about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of medicine specializing in sleep problems at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S.
She was inspired to start the course after giving lectures on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of the day a girl came up to me and said: ‘Why am I just being told now, in my final year?’
The girl said no one ever told me about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," she told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first launched this year, explains to students the essence of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic outcomes, as well as improving their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of university health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding students who were severely sleep deprived throughout the week.
This one-hour course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In one session there was an overview of the dorm room, where students clicked on coffee cups, curtains, exercise pants, and books to get an explanation of the effects of caffeine and lights, as well as how athletic outcomes were affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of sleep routines.
In another section, participants were given an explanation of how long sleep deprivation could increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
"We know this won't change students' behavior instantly.
But we believe that they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know the effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes on health," Czeisler said.
The culture of being proud of the 'badang' still exists, he said, plus that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Ensuring you sleep enough, with good quality, should be a ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he says — even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain activate hunger mode, inducing continued hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California resident who studied chemistry and physical biology who helped Professor Czeisler design the course, had taken one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that this course had opened his eyes and inspired him to organize courses for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes that all graduate students will be instructed to complete a similar program of study before joining a competitive institution.
Prof Czeisler recommends that students should consider setting a sleep alarm, also a wake alarm, and be aware of the effects of the ‘blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can shift your circadian rhythm out of its regulatory path causing sleep problems.
