Red Tide: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
A recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission showed a general decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, uneven build-up conditions were reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas – which signaled a decrease in concentrations.
A group of Red Tide extends approximately 130 miles of coastline from north of Pinellas to the southern Lee area.
The clusters can be found about 10 miles off the coast of the Hillsborough area, but on some sites relative to last week.
Red Tide has also been observed in the Pasco region.
Moderate or offshore concentrations of Pinellas region have been reported last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough region, background to high concentrations in Manatee region, background to high concentrations on or offshore Sarasota region, background to moderate concentrations in Charlotte region, background to high concentrations on or offshore Lee region, and low concentrations in Collier region.
Respiratory irritation continues to be reported from the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier regions.
There have been no reports of respiratory irritation in Northwest Florida over the past week.
